<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Salix</i> <i>nivalis</i> is dominant in the dwarf shrub and herbaceous layers with shrubs <i>Salix</i> <i>petrophila</i> and herbs:<i>Achillea</i> <i>millefolium</i>, <i>Carex</i> <i>subnigricans</i>, <i>Festuca</i> <i>brachyphylla</i>, <i>Phlox</i> <i>covillei</i>, <i>Pyrrocoma</i> <i>apargioides</i>, <i>Rhodiola</i> <i>integrifolia</i>, <i>Solidago</i> <i>multiradiata</i> or <i>Trisetum</i> <i>spicatum</i>. </div>
</div>

		
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 30 cm; canopy is intermittent to continuous. Herbaceous layer is open to continuous at the same height as <i>S. nivalis.</i> </div>
</div>

		
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Bases of alpine cirques, solifluction lobes. Soils are thin and rocky. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Salix nivalis</i> as a FACW plant. </div>
</div>

		
