<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Salix nivalis </i>is a deciduous, prostrate shrub that is usually less than 10 cm tall. Its leaves are shiny green above and pale gray-green and glabrous below. <i>S. nivalis </i>is part of the circumpolar <i>S. reticulata </i>complex that is treated differently by authors (Argus 1997, USDA NRCS 2008), including <i>S. reticulata </i>that grows in Canada and Alaska, and <i>S. nivalis </i>that occurs from British Columbia, across to the Rocky Mountains and to California. <br/>
<br/>
The <i>Salix </i>( <i>reticulata, nivalis</i>) alliance occurs in alpine areas in Washington and Colorado, where snow melts early and frost action is a disturbance feature (NatureServe 2007a). The southernmost occurrences in the range are in local environmental settings similar to those in the northern Rockies, where stands are more common than in California. They carpet active solifluction slopes and sites with frost-heave action, and they may be subirrigated by snowfields above the stands. The <i>Salix nivalis </i>alliance in California may be relictual. <i>S. nivalis </i>(a CNPS 2.3 list plant) so far is known from only five occurrences in the state. </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> The alliance occurs along the Sierra Nevada crest (M261Eo, Er), usually on metamorphic substrates from Dunderberg Peak near Conway Summit to Mount Morrison in the Convict Lake area where Pemble (1970) described a <i>Salix nivalis</i> association on slate and marble. Stands occur on Dana Plateau in granite and in the Virginia Lakes area on metamorphic substrates (Sawyer and Keeler-Wolf 2007). A stand sampled at Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b) contained a small amount of <i>S. petrophila</i> with associates <i>Carex subnigricans, Rhodiola integrifolia,</i> and <i>Solidago multiradiata</i>. The stands of <i>S. nivalis</i> may represent a few individual clones that have spread as mats in the alpine zone, and as a vegetation type, it is rare in California. We need more sampling and analysis to determine differences between related types, such as the <i>Salix reticulata</i> and <i>Salix nivalis</i> alliances in the Rocky Mountains. </div>
</div>

	

    
